WEBVTT

00:11.330 --> 00:12.311
Hey, what's up everybody?

00:12.351 --> 00:15.236
For those of you who don't know me, my name is Jeremy Treat.

00:15.376 --> 00:17.699
I'm one of the pastors here at Reality LA.

00:18.360 --> 00:23.507
And if you've got a Bible, go ahead and grab it and open it up to the book of Philippians.

00:24.128 --> 00:27.593
And as you turn there, I want to take a minute to talk about the offering.

00:28.154 --> 00:34.243
Offering really is a good way of talking about what we're doing here because our giving is an act of worship to God.

00:34.803 --> 00:39.410
We ultimately give to God for the work of God and to the glory of God.

00:39.842 --> 00:46.210
And this enables us to then fulfill our mission as a church and to practically meet needs in our community and throughout the city.

00:46.770 --> 00:50.435
And there's so many needs right now in the midst of this pandemic.

00:50.515 --> 00:54.299
And so it might be easy for you to think, well, by myself, what can I do?

00:54.359 --> 00:59.686
Well, there is only so much that we can do as individuals, but together we can do a lot.

00:59.946 --> 01:05.232
And so this is a way that we give to be able to show God's love and provision in so many ways.

01:05.332 --> 01:06.674
If you want to give

01:06.818 --> 01:09.321
The way to do that is through the push pay app.

01:09.441 --> 01:12.744
So if you have a smartphone, you just go to the app store and look for push pay.

01:13.325 --> 01:18.950
And then once you download that, you search for reality LA and it's pretty easy to set up and give there.

01:19.711 --> 01:20.872
And thank you for your giving.

01:21.092 --> 01:23.795
The Lord is doing a good work and you're involved in it in that way.

01:24.636 --> 01:28.260
Okay, let's grab our Bibles and look at Philippians chapter one.

01:28.720 --> 01:34.546
We're in a series right now in the book of Philippians that we're calling Defiant Joy because in this pandemic,

01:34.690 --> 01:38.496
It's Jesus, not our circumstances, that determines our joy.

01:39.097 --> 01:47.230
And so today I'll be preaching on Philippians 1, verses 12 through 18, and we will be talking about resilient faith.

01:47.410 --> 01:51.156
So I'll read that passage for us, and then I'll open our time in prayer.

01:52.017 --> 01:54.962
Philippians 1, verses 12 through 18.

01:54.982 --> 02:02.674
I want you to know, brothers, that what has happened to me has really served to advance the gospel.

02:03.330 --> 02:09.840
so that it has become known throughout the whole imperial guard and to all the rest that my imprisonment is for Christ.

02:10.881 --> 02:17.932
And most of the brothers, having become confident in the Lord by my imprisonment, are much more bold to speak the word without fear.

02:19.073 --> 02:23.380
Some indeed preach Christ from envy and rivalry, but others from good will.

02:24.141 --> 02:28.487
The latter do it out of love, knowing that I am put here for the defense of the gospel.

02:29.108 --> 02:33.074
The former proclaimed Christ out of selfish ambition, not sincerely,

02:33.218 --> 02:35.621
But thinking to afflict me in my imprisonment.

02:36.181 --> 02:36.602
What then?

02:37.523 --> 02:42.809
Only that in every way, whether in pretense or in truth, Christ is proclaimed.

02:42.929 --> 02:44.651
And in that, I rejoice.

02:45.552 --> 02:46.373
This is God's word.

02:46.834 --> 02:47.554
Let's pray together.

02:50.298 --> 03:01.170
Lord, as we proclaim Christ during this time, we pray that the gospel would advance in our hearts and our communities and in this city.

03:01.666 --> 03:02.427
Lord, we need you.

03:02.487 --> 03:10.217
We are desperate for you, especially in this time where there's so much suffering, there's so much uncertainty, there's so much loss.

03:10.757 --> 03:17.125
We look to you as our hope, as our Savior, as our King who is ruling right now.

03:17.987 --> 03:27.478
God, we pray that as your word is preached, that your spirit would be at work within us, bringing change in our lives, bringing renewal and restoration.

03:27.959 --> 03:30.322
And God, would you draw us into the work

03:30.466 --> 03:31.327
that you're doing.

03:31.347 --> 03:34.652
We look to you and we pray this in Jesus name.

03:35.253 --> 03:35.553
Amen.

03:36.975 --> 03:37.376
Amen.

03:38.397 --> 03:42.102
Well, now is the time more than ever that we need resilience.

03:43.063 --> 03:51.034
And if you look that word up in the dictionary, it will tell you that resilience is the ability to withstand or recover from difficult conditions.

03:51.835 --> 03:53.998
But I like to think about it like bamboo.

03:54.780 --> 03:59.506
See, some plants or trees are really strong, but they're not very flexible.

04:00.098 --> 04:03.442
While there's other plants that are really flexible but they're not strong.

04:04.183 --> 04:07.447
Well bamboo is strong and it's flexible.

04:08.188 --> 04:13.054
If strong winds come, the bamboo can bend but not be broken.

04:13.094 --> 04:18.922
It can actually be pressed all the way to the ground but it bounces back to where it was before.

04:19.422 --> 04:20.804
That is resilience.

04:21.405 --> 04:23.187
And that's exactly what we need right now.

04:23.988 --> 04:28.914
We've been bent and pressed and left wondering whether we'll be able to bounce back at all.

04:29.474 --> 04:38.503
And so the question is this, how can we withstand and recover from the loss and uncertainty that we're all experiencing right now because of the coronavirus?

04:39.464 --> 04:48.713
Well, in our passage today in Philippians 1, we're going to see that this kind of internal resilience is ultimately found in the gospel.

04:49.714 --> 04:53.879
And for the apostle Paul, he's experiencing some very difficult conditions.

04:54.539 --> 04:57.202
He's been imprisoned by a pagan government

04:57.410 --> 05:00.135
And now he's being attacked by fellow Christians.

05:00.916 --> 05:02.960
It's hard to imagine a tougher situation.

05:03.020 --> 05:10.814
And yet Paul has this unflinching confidence in God and a defiant joy in the face of adversity.

05:11.636 --> 05:17.466
So we're going to see how the gospel produced resilience for Paul in imprisonment and in opposition.

05:17.526 --> 05:21.874
And then we'll apply that to our situation today in a pandemic.

05:22.370 --> 05:27.740
So first, let's look and see how the gospel produced resilience for Paul in imprisonment.

05:28.161 --> 05:30.486
Let me read to you verse 12 once more.

05:30.526 --> 05:38.161
Paul says, I want you to know, brothers, that what has happened to me has really served to advance the gospel.

05:38.902 --> 05:42.930
So he's in prison, but the question is, why is he there?

05:43.426 --> 06:01.569
Well, from one perspective, he's there because he got arrested for preaching the gospel and then one government official kind of passed him on to the next and he appealed to Rome and they passed him on to the next and then eventually guards placed him in the prison, probably attaching him by chain to a Roman guard.

06:02.049 --> 06:04.112
At one level, that's why he's in prison.

06:04.753 --> 06:07.857
But Paul's saying, there's a deeper reason that I'm here.

06:08.638 --> 06:12.242
I'm not here because of Caesar's power, but because of God's power.

06:12.770 --> 06:16.035
I'm not here for Rome's purposes, but for God's purposes.

06:16.556 --> 06:18.599
This isn't about stopping the gospel.

06:18.679 --> 06:20.902
This is actually advancing the gospel.

06:21.783 --> 06:23.186
And this is incredible, isn't it?

06:23.206 --> 06:28.433
I mean, the worst possible situation is pagan government is attacking him.

06:28.473 --> 06:32.860
People in the church are attacking him and Paul doesn't ask, is God at work?

06:33.621 --> 06:36.165
No, he asks, how is God at work?

06:36.986 --> 06:40.651
He believes in the absolute sovereignty of God.

06:41.272 --> 06:42.354
He knows.

06:42.562 --> 06:45.805
that God works all things together for the good of those who love him.

06:45.845 --> 06:51.470
He knows God is working out his plan that he established before the foundations of the world.

06:52.291 --> 06:52.972
But here's the key.

06:54.033 --> 06:57.896
It's not that God is accomplishing his purposes in spite of hardship.

06:58.597 --> 07:02.701
No, God accomplishes his purposes through hardship.

07:03.602 --> 07:07.766
That's the key to having the kind of resilience that we need.

07:09.327 --> 07:10.408
Think about what Paul says.

07:11.169 --> 07:12.530
My imprisonment

07:12.706 --> 07:13.648
is for Christ.

07:14.289 --> 07:15.050
How can he say that?

07:15.110 --> 07:17.033
Come on, is that just spin?

07:17.073 --> 07:22.081
Is he just making a bad situation sound good to help weak people get through it?

07:22.101 --> 07:26.749
No, the gospel truly is being advanced through his imprisonment.

07:26.789 --> 07:32.218
Let me show you three ways that the gospel is being advanced through his imprisonment here.

07:32.258 --> 07:36.966
And the first is, is that through his imprisonment, he's able to witness to the Roman guards.

07:37.567 --> 07:39.570
Look at verse 13, he says,

07:40.066 --> 07:48.798
so that it has become known throughout the whole Imperial Guard and to all the rest that my imprisonment is for Christ.

07:49.399 --> 07:56.568
So these guards that it's talking about there would have included up to 9,000 Roman guards and he's saying they're all talking about it.

07:56.588 --> 08:01.115
They've all heard, have you heard of this apostle who's imprisoned for Christ?

08:02.056 --> 08:06.642
But while it would have spread broad to many people who were talking about it,

08:06.850 --> 08:12.258
I want you to specifically think about the Roman guards who are with Paul and responsible for him.

08:12.959 --> 08:14.702
I mean, Paul's got a history of this, right?

08:14.762 --> 08:20.410
Remember back in Acts 16 at the beginning of the church plant of the church in Philippi?

08:20.831 --> 08:22.093
How did it start?

08:22.133 --> 08:28.402
Well, one of the key members early on in the church was a jailer who Paul converted.

08:28.802 --> 08:34.690
Him and Silas were singing songs and praying, and then they convert this jailer.

08:34.750 --> 08:38.475
I mean, can you imagine the jailer back in Philippi hearing about this now?

08:38.555 --> 08:39.296
Paul's in prison.

08:39.456 --> 08:41.379
Oh, I bet he's gonna convert those guys.

08:41.920 --> 08:46.946
Like he just knows there must have been, Paul must have been just like licking his chops.

08:47.046 --> 08:51.953
Like all of a sudden, you know, he's chained to this Roman garden.

08:52.013 --> 08:54.116
He's probably thinking, I'm not chained to you.

08:54.176 --> 08:55.698
You're chained to me.

08:56.002 --> 08:57.805
Let me tell you about Jesus.

08:58.286 --> 09:00.429
Have you heard about this Messiah?

09:00.470 --> 09:09.705
He's the one who was killed by your co-workers, Roman centurions and yet who said, Father forgive them for they know not what they do.

09:10.086 --> 09:15.755
He's probably saying to them, did you know that he rose from the grave that even death couldn't stop Jesus?

09:16.837 --> 09:22.226
So Paul is preaching the gospel to the guards who are right there with them and think about it.

09:22.786 --> 09:26.309
How else would anyone preach the gospel to those people?

09:27.070 --> 09:40.143
Paul can look at that and say clearly, my imprisonment is advancing the gospel, but not only as that happening through sharing with the guards, but also by strengthening fellow believers to speak boldly.

09:40.643 --> 09:42.145
So look at verse 14.

09:42.165 --> 09:51.794
He goes on and he says, most of the brothers, having become confident in the Lord by my imprisonment, are much more bold to speak the word without fear.

09:52.322 --> 09:55.486
So many Christians were timid and scared during this time.

09:55.546 --> 09:56.247
It makes sense.

09:56.347 --> 09:58.169
You could get persecuted for your faith.

09:58.810 --> 10:03.115
But Paul was so bold in doing this that it emboldens them.

10:03.155 --> 10:04.998
They're feeling more brave.

10:05.018 --> 10:10.004
They're willing to go out and share the word and proclaim Christ without fear.

10:10.044 --> 10:12.046
And so think about what's happened.

10:12.066 --> 10:15.090
You've gone from Paul preaching boldly

10:15.202 --> 10:22.312
Well, now he's in prison, but now you've gone from just one man preaching boldly to dozens, maybe hundreds who are out there preaching boldly.

10:22.413 --> 10:25.517
So the gospel is clearly advancing in that way.

10:25.537 --> 10:35.192
There's one other way that I want to show you though, that the gospel is advancing through Paul's imprisonment and you kind of have to zoom out to see the broader context of this a little bit more.

10:35.232 --> 10:39.237
Paul is likely in prison in Rome.

10:39.939 --> 10:42.322
And if you go back and read through the book of Acts,

10:42.562 --> 10:47.748
Paul was bent on getting to Rome, the most influential city in the ancient world.

10:47.848 --> 10:50.931
He wanted to be able to get there to preach the gospel.

10:51.191 --> 10:52.393
And how does he get there?

10:52.433 --> 10:56.437
Well, he's taken, he's escorted by these Roman guards.

10:57.018 --> 11:02.383
So it's clear that the gospel is being advanced through his imprisonment.

11:02.984 --> 11:10.232
But we've still got to ask the question, how could Paul have such confidence in such dire circumstances?

11:10.993 --> 11:12.114
Well, I'll tell you,

11:12.482 --> 11:15.146
He'd been reading the Old Testament for a long time.

11:15.987 --> 11:19.832
He'd been reading stories of the kind of God that he worshiped.

11:20.513 --> 11:22.336
He would have read about Joseph.

11:23.077 --> 11:26.101
Remember what happened to Joseph in the book of Genesis?

11:26.682 --> 11:30.227
He's sold into slavery by his brothers.

11:30.267 --> 11:31.649
He gets thrown into a pit.

11:32.029 --> 11:34.533
He's eventually placed in prison.

11:34.993 --> 11:36.575
He's in prison for years.

11:37.096 --> 11:41.362
And yet it's very clear looking back at the Lord is at work in all of this.

11:41.666 --> 11:44.170
And so you get to the end of the book of Genesis.

11:44.951 --> 11:52.903
And Joseph says to his brothers what you meant for evil, God meant for good, for the saving of many lives.

11:53.684 --> 11:56.188
Paul knew about these stories and he was encouraged by it.

11:56.208 --> 12:08.146
Maybe Paul was thinking about the times that he'd read about David, hiding in the caves, isolated, confused, threatened, and yet knowing that God was preparing him to be king.

12:08.642 --> 12:20.338
Maybe Paul was thinking about the time where the prophet Jeremiah was thrown into a dungeon and yet he continued to boldly proclaim God's word to his people of being faithful and exile.

12:21.399 --> 12:30.591
See, when we read the Bible, we are reading a story of a God who accomplishes his purposes, not in spite of hardship, but through hardship.

12:31.312 --> 12:34.997
And the pinnacle of that story, of course, is the cross of Christ.

12:35.638 --> 12:38.642
I mean, there's not a worse situation imaginable.

12:39.234 --> 12:41.978
than the world rebelling against its Creator.

12:42.719 --> 12:47.886
And when the Son of God comes in love, they kill Him out of hatred and pride.

12:48.827 --> 12:56.898
And yet, while the cross is the most ugly display of our sin, it's the most beautiful display of God's grace.

12:57.599 --> 13:02.706
Because it was there on the cross where Jesus took on our sin to blot it out.

13:03.010 --> 13:13.185
It was there on the cross where Jesus accomplished victory through sacrifice and it was there on the cross where Jesus showed his perfect love and justice.

13:14.186 --> 13:25.143
That's why Paul can be imprisoned and yet have the confidence of a man who's been set free because he has this faith in the crucified and risen Christ.

13:26.525 --> 13:30.130
And faith doesn't just mean believing in something that you can't see.

13:30.786 --> 13:34.391
Faith is looking at things from a different perspective altogether.

13:35.613 --> 13:40.761
Paul was in prison, but from his perspective, he could say, I'm not a captive prisoner.

13:41.061 --> 13:42.403
You're my captive audience.

13:43.304 --> 13:46.229
He could say, you didn't drag me to a place I didn't want to go.

13:46.249 --> 13:51.677
I was escorted on Rome's dime, by the way, to the place that I wanted to go all along.

13:52.137 --> 13:55.883
He could say, your persecution is not slowing down Christ's mission.

13:56.263 --> 13:58.066
It's propelling it forward.

13:58.530 --> 14:03.798
That's why Paul can say, my imprisonment is for Christ.

14:04.780 --> 14:11.730
Now, I want to apply this to our circumstance today and what we are all experiencing.

14:11.790 --> 14:19.803
And think about it like this, imprisonment for Paul was an unwanted circumstance that was placed on him against his will, right?

14:20.764 --> 14:25.632
And we all have circumstances that are thrust upon us against our will.

14:25.912 --> 14:27.154
And yet Paul can say,

14:27.650 --> 14:29.712
my imprisonment is for Christ.

14:30.513 --> 14:37.081
So what would it look like for you to take into account the circumstances that have been thrust upon you and to say, it's for Christ?

14:37.822 --> 14:42.527
Well, there's one that most of us have in common and that's we're in quarantine right now.

14:43.268 --> 14:46.552
How can we say my quarantine is for Christ?

14:47.172 --> 14:51.137
I mean, you know, Paul's in prison, we're in quarantine.

14:51.157 --> 14:54.961
You can't really compare prison to quarantine.

14:55.081 --> 14:55.602
I mean,

14:55.714 --> 14:57.877
I've gotten a tele in my house.

14:58.117 --> 14:59.719
And it's the Costco size, all right?

14:59.759 --> 15:03.083
So I can't really say like, I can't complain about being trapped there.

15:03.804 --> 15:08.249
And yet there are similarities right between quarantine and prison.

15:08.269 --> 15:10.272
I mean, isolation, you're stuck inside.

15:10.312 --> 15:12.314
It's an unwanted circumstance.

15:13.215 --> 15:16.860
So what does it look like for us to say my quarantine is for Christ?

15:17.621 --> 15:20.024
Or to be able to say my sickness is for Christ.

15:20.604 --> 15:23.047
My unemployment is for Christ.

15:23.808 --> 15:25.170
And you can say that.

15:25.794 --> 15:26.936
Because God is at work.

15:27.817 --> 15:30.501
You may be alone, but you're not abandoned.

15:31.482 --> 15:34.206
You may feel the pressure, but you're not crushed.

15:34.947 --> 15:37.430
You may have sorrow, but you're not dismayed.

15:38.211 --> 15:42.637
And you may feel the uncertainty of tomorrow, but you don't have to be afraid of it.

15:42.678 --> 15:48.786
The gospel produces resilience precisely for times like these.

15:49.762 --> 15:53.727
All right, so we see how the gospel produces resilience in Paul's imprisonment.

15:54.207 --> 15:58.012
Now let's see how the gospel produces resilience amidst opposition.

15:58.873 --> 16:01.616
Let me read to you verses 15 through 18.

16:02.257 --> 16:08.744
Paul says this, some indeed preach Christ from envy and rivalry, but others from good will.

16:09.545 --> 16:13.690
The latter do it out of love, knowing that I am put here for the defense of the gospel.

16:14.391 --> 16:17.234
The former proclaimed Christ out of selfish ambition.

16:17.570 --> 16:21.435
Not sincerely, but thinking to afflict me in my imprisonment."

16:21.455 --> 16:21.836
What then?

16:22.557 --> 16:28.705
Only that in every way, whether in pretense or in truth, Christ is proclaimed, and in that, I rejoice.

16:29.746 --> 16:31.668
Now, I want you to understand what was going on here.

16:31.769 --> 16:39.178
First of all, I don't think he's talking about false teachers and non-Christians who are proclaiming a false gospel.

16:39.739 --> 16:45.106
He has other words for that, and Paul speaks very strongly against that when that's the case.

16:45.378 --> 16:51.466
No, he's talking about Christians who are actually proclaiming the gospel, but their motives are off.

16:52.387 --> 16:58.254
And what I think is going on here is that in Paul's absence, it appears that other preachers are jockeying for position.

16:58.935 --> 17:05.964
They're fighting for prominence and worldly honor, and they're putting Paul down in order to build themselves up.

17:06.985 --> 17:10.630
So, so Paul looks at that and why is he saying this though?

17:10.650 --> 17:13.714
Well, I mean, he acknowledges it for what it is, like gross, right?

17:13.858 --> 17:16.321
like people are preaching for bad motives, whatever.

17:16.701 --> 17:19.505
But his point is Christ has preached nonetheless.

17:19.525 --> 17:26.573
I mean, it says if he's saying, listen, God spoke through a donkey in the Old Testament, he can use a preacher with mixed motives.

17:27.795 --> 17:30.338
And here's what struck me about these verses.

17:31.539 --> 17:35.744
Sometimes Christians can be more brutal than centurions.

17:37.186 --> 17:38.928
I mean, Paul is in prison, right?

17:39.168 --> 17:40.530
The guards are one thing.

17:40.994 --> 17:44.400
But his fellow Christians are taking shots at him in this.

17:45.121 --> 17:47.445
How hypocritical and hurtful.

17:48.827 --> 17:54.777
And I say this because I know that many of you have wounds from people like this in the church.

17:55.438 --> 17:57.482
It's not just preachers with bad motives.

17:57.522 --> 18:04.233
Those preachers who are preaching out of envy and rivalry create churches that are tribalistic and prideful.

18:04.313 --> 18:07.058
That leads to a lot of wounds for a lot of people.

18:07.554 --> 18:11.279
And so if you've experienced that, then I'm deeply sorry for that.

18:12.020 --> 18:13.422
I want to acknowledge that.

18:14.804 --> 18:16.066
But let's look at the passage here.

18:16.166 --> 18:19.310
What is the point that Paul is making in this text?

18:19.811 --> 18:22.595
The point is, is that the gospel advances nonetheless.

18:23.456 --> 18:30.546
In other words, God uses an imperfect church to accomplish his perfect plans.

18:31.458 --> 18:37.447
The Bible is not a story of God finding perfect people, but of saving sinful people.

18:38.428 --> 18:39.891
And this gives me so much hope.

18:40.812 --> 18:44.277
I can look at the church in America and there's lots of problems.

18:44.878 --> 18:48.944
There's lots of mixed motives in preachers and in Christians, right?

18:48.964 --> 18:54.512
I can look at our church and I can see lots of problems and I can see lots of mixed motives even in my own heart.

18:55.434 --> 18:58.418
And yet I can know that God is at work.

18:59.010 --> 19:01.212
God's not looking for perfect people.

19:01.292 --> 19:05.216
He's looking for broken people who are willing to trust in Him.

19:06.337 --> 19:12.203
This is the kind of faith we need to be resilient in a time like this.

19:13.865 --> 19:18.390
So we've seen how the gospel produces resilience in imprisonment and in opposition.

19:18.930 --> 19:21.993
But what about in a pandemic?

19:22.014 --> 19:26.418
Well, first of all, we've got to acknowledge that this is just hard.

19:27.970 --> 19:34.458
We as Christians, we can have a sense of realism about what's going on right now.

19:34.498 --> 19:35.320
Paul does that.

19:35.920 --> 19:38.504
He doesn't minimize the fact that he's in prison.

19:38.584 --> 19:42.709
He doesn't leave that out when he writes this letter to the Philippians.

19:43.550 --> 19:45.433
And we can be honest about all of this.

19:45.493 --> 19:46.114
It's brutal.

19:46.374 --> 19:49.798
And the hard part is it seems like we've got a long way to go.

19:49.818 --> 19:52.642
I mean, to put it bluntly, this sucks.

19:53.523 --> 19:55.666
I mean, for me personally, I miss people.

19:56.258 --> 20:01.845
I'm so tired of Zoom and I'm lamenting the loss all around.

20:02.846 --> 20:05.830
But I want to remind you that the Lord has not forgotten about us.

20:06.791 --> 20:09.495
And we don't need to ask, is God at work?

20:09.655 --> 20:13.560
No, the question is, how is God at work?

20:13.580 --> 20:15.723
And we can ask that question because we know this.

20:15.923 --> 20:21.650
Remember, he accomplishes his purposes, not in spite of hardship, but through hardship.

20:22.754 --> 20:26.079
And there's a lot that's stopped in our world right now.

20:26.680 --> 20:30.046
But I want to remind you that the mission of Christ has not stopped.

20:31.308 --> 20:34.172
There's so many things going on right now.

20:34.212 --> 20:35.514
There are evidence of that.

20:36.195 --> 20:42.926
I mean, just in the last month, I have heard many stories of people getting saved and having their lives changed by Jesus.

20:43.888 --> 20:45.971
We've got new people joining our church.

20:46.472 --> 20:50.418
We've got a new community group that's starting up soon and probably more to come.

20:50.530 --> 20:52.352
We're crying out in prayer.

20:52.412 --> 20:56.457
We've got regional prayer coming up this week next week or in a couple of weeks.

20:56.477 --> 20:59.922
We're going to be appointing several new deacons in our church.

21:00.442 --> 21:01.944
The mission goes on.

21:02.104 --> 21:03.186
God is at work.

21:03.306 --> 21:05.348
The gospel is advancing.

21:06.029 --> 21:08.693
The gospel can't be stopped by imprisonment.

21:08.813 --> 21:11.136
The gospel can't be stopped by opposition.

21:11.536 --> 21:13.539
The gospel can't be stopped by disease.

21:13.639 --> 21:16.242
The gospel can't be stopped by recession.

21:17.154 --> 21:21.799
No, the Lord is calling us to move forward, to advance even in this.

21:23.221 --> 21:32.872
I do want to qualify one thing that I've said in the last few weeks based on the context, especially this passage that we're looking at in Philippians 1.

21:32.892 --> 21:38.478
I've talked about how this is a time as a church where we don't want to just survive, but we want to thrive.

21:39.219 --> 21:45.746
And I really believe that, but I want to make sure that when we hear thriving as a church,

21:45.986 --> 21:57.017
that we don't hear that in worldly means of like bigger and better and flashy and everything's awesome and easy and safe and comfortable.

21:57.037 --> 22:02.102
No, we see Paul here saying that the gospel is advancing.

22:02.863 --> 22:04.224
The church is growing.

22:04.284 --> 22:05.185
There's life.

22:05.325 --> 22:07.167
It's thriving in that sense.

22:07.187 --> 22:08.709
And yet he's in prison.

22:09.410 --> 22:13.874
The church in Philippi is being persecuted in different ways.

22:14.530 --> 22:16.633
So I really believe that we can advance.

22:16.714 --> 22:22.022
I mean, the word that's used here for advancing in Philippians 1 means to move forward, to progress.

22:22.723 --> 22:27.331
And I believe that we can do that, but that means us learning to depend on the Lord more than we ever have.

22:28.112 --> 22:41.714
That means us trusting in God, growing in our faith through this hardship, looking to Him, having more of a heart of compassion for the hurting around us and being a part of the work that the Lord is doing in this city.

22:42.594 --> 22:47.200
I mean, this pandemic has been a disruption to everything in our world.

22:48.081 --> 22:53.167
And yet I think that the Lord has used it to reveal some things in our lives that we might otherwise miss.

22:54.469 --> 22:59.716
Being forced to slow down shows us how addicted we all were to accomplishments.

23:00.797 --> 23:09.027
The quiet makes us look back and realize that we had so much noise in our lives that we rarely reflected on what's most important.

23:10.049 --> 23:11.250
The isolation.

23:11.490 --> 23:17.139
makes us recognize how we've taken relationships for granted in so many ways.

23:18.241 --> 23:28.698
So much has been stripped away during this time and we're faced with the question, what are we without all of our accomplishments and our social lives and our work?

23:30.481 --> 23:35.509
And those things, they're not bad things, work and social lives and accomplishments, they're not bad things.

23:36.230 --> 23:38.834
But God is teaching us what matters most in life

23:39.202 --> 23:42.007
is not dependent on changing circumstances.

23:42.888 --> 23:44.170
God is with you.

23:44.952 --> 23:46.354
God loves you.

23:47.055 --> 23:52.664
And God is teaching you and forming you and shaping you during this time.

23:54.147 --> 24:01.800
Now I started off talking about the meaning of resilience and I even gave you a definition for the word.

24:01.880 --> 24:03.282
What I didn't tell you is that

24:03.810 --> 24:10.817
The English word resilience comes from the Latin word that literally means to bounce back.

24:12.418 --> 24:16.302
It's this idea of when you get knocked down, you get back up, you bounce back.

24:17.283 --> 24:21.007
Well, there's no greater example of resilience than this.

24:22.148 --> 24:26.492
Jesus was crucified, and then he was placed in a tomb.

24:27.573 --> 24:32.818
And three days later, he walked out of that tomb, conquering death

24:33.026 --> 24:33.667
itself.

24:34.669 --> 24:37.092
This is the great reversal.

24:37.873 --> 24:41.599
They tried to humiliate Jesus and it became his exaltation.

24:41.619 --> 24:46.367
They tried to make death his end, but it turned into a doorway to life.

24:47.128 --> 24:53.618
He took on all the hatred of the world and turned it into the greatest act of love for the world.

24:54.639 --> 24:59.607
And so the main message that I want you to hear today isn't be resilient.

25:00.068 --> 25:01.490
What I want you to hear

25:01.954 --> 25:06.821
is that Christ is resilient, and I want to call you to trust in Him.

25:07.662 --> 25:12.890
That's how we can be a resilient people in such a trying time as this.

25:13.631 --> 25:14.352
Let's pray together.

25:16.956 --> 25:29.394
God, we thank you for what you've done for us in sending your son, Jesus Christ, that He entered into our pain, He entered into our uncertainty, He entered into our brokenness,

25:31.106 --> 25:35.573
And he went to the cross taking on our sin so that we could be forgiven.

25:35.633 --> 25:41.282
And he rose from the grave so that we can have new life and abundant life and eternal life.

25:41.462 --> 25:42.724
And we can have that today.

25:42.784 --> 25:49.274
And so God, we thank you that when we rebelled against you that you didn't give up on us.

25:50.737 --> 25:55.464
Thank you that when we ran from you, you kept pursuing us.

25:56.746 --> 25:59.410
And so God, we pray that you would give us faith today.

26:00.322 --> 26:02.825
to surrender to you, to trust in you.

26:03.726 --> 26:08.532
And Lord, as we do that, would you produce resilience at a heart?

26:09.673 --> 26:10.675
God, we're weary.

26:11.596 --> 26:12.417
We're tired.

26:13.859 --> 26:18.004
We don't know when this is going to change or how this is going to play out.

26:18.104 --> 26:23.891
And so we look to you and we pray that in our weakness that you would make us strong.

26:24.892 --> 26:29.618
God, I pray for those who are on the verge of giving up, that they would press on.

26:30.210 --> 26:35.428
that they would stand firm, that they would endure as they look to Christ.

26:35.830 --> 26:37.174
We pray this in His name.

26:37.857 --> 26:38.258
Amen.

